article.headline: Artest scores 27 in win
article.linkText: Pacers continue road to success in Toronto
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) -- Ron Artest couldn't believe the Indiana Pacers have one more road win than they managed all of last season. Artest scored 27 points, Jermaine O'Neal added 20 and Al Harrington 19 as the Eastern Conference-leading Pacers beat the Toronto Raptors 83-77 on Friday night. "For real? Wow," said Artest, whose team is 17-9 on the road. "That says a lot. For us to have more road wins already, I didn't realize that. That shows the team is maturing." Jamaal Tinsley scored five of Indiana's last seven points after Toronto closed within two. O'Neal, who vowed to have a better game after going 6-for-20 from the field in a loss to New York on Tuesday, added 14 rebounds as the Pacers won for the fourth time in five games. "We're very mature right now," said O'Neal, whose team went 16-25 on the road last season. "We understand that we may lose a game at home in the playoffs, and we have to be able to go into a tough arena and win a game. "Right now, we're just setting a tone. We're sending a message not only to ourselves, but to the rest of the league that we can win on the road, no matter who it is." Indiana coach Rick Carlisle, who took over from the fired Isiah Thomas, said one of their goals was to become a better road team. The Pacers were eliminated in the first round of the playoffs the last three years. "The statistics show that teams that can win on the road during the regular season have a better chance to advance in the playoffs," Carlisle said. "Our No. 1 goal is to get out of the first round. Winning on the road is one of the ways we felt we could do it. Our guys have done a great job." Donyell Marshall had 24 points and 10 rebounds for the Raptors. Layups by Marshall and Vince Carter cut Indiana's lead to two with 2:43 left, but Tinsley's 3-pointer gave Indiana a 79-74 edge with 2:23 left. "That was a gutsy shot," said Carlisle, who drew up the play for O'Neal. "I give Jamaal a lot of credit. He stepped into it with confidence and it was a huge shot. It was the biggest shot of the game." The Raptors missed their next three shots before Tinsley made two free throws to make it a seven-point lead with 23 seconds remaining. Marshall followed with a 3-pointer with 15 seconds left, but Tinsley grabbed an offensive rebound after Reggie Miller, an 88-percent foul shooter, missed two free throws. Miller went to the line again and made both, giving Indiana a six-point lead with six seconds left. "They are a good basketball team that executes," Toronto coach Kevin O'Neill said. "We had our chances at the end. Tinsley made a huge shot, but we still had chances." Raptors rookie center Chris Bosh missed his second straight game with a sprained left ankle. Robert Archibald, who replaced Bosh at center, had two points while backup center Jerome Moiso went 0-for-7 from the field and did not score. Alvin Williams cut Indiana's lead to two with a jumper in the third quarter, but Tinsley followed with an open 3-pointer, sparking a 13-2 run. Harrington capped it with a fast-break layup, giving Indiana a 13-point lead. Artest had 10 points in the first quarter and Harrington had 11 in the second as Indiana led by as many as 14 in the first half. Toronto cut the lead to five at halftime.

Game notes
Kevin O'Neill spent the previous two seasons as an assistant coach under Carlisle in Detroit. After the game, O'Neill told Carlisle to come to Toronto's locker room for a light beer. ... Official Bill Kennedy screamed at Jermaine O'Neal in the second quarter. "I'm trying to do something! Back off!" as O'Neal stared at Kennedy following a timeout.
